The summary statistics and bar chart reveal a striking finding: in the vast majority of simulations, stepwise regression selects at least one "significant" predictor even though every variable is pure noise. The mean number of selected predictors reflects the expected false positive rate given 20 candidate predictors. This demonstration is the strongest argument against relying on automatic selection for confirmatory research --- the method is designed to find patterns, and it will find them whether or not they are real.

