Compare the mean RMSE values across the three models. If the theory-driven model achieves comparable or better out-of-sample RMSE than the stepwise model, this supports the confirmatory approach --- the model specified by theory generalizes as well as (or better than) a data-driven selection. The standard deviation of RMSE across folds indicates how stable the model's predictions are. A model with low mean RMSE but high variability across folds may be less reliable than one with slightly higher mean RMSE but greater stability. The key lesson: cross-validation provides an honest estimate of predictive performance that penalizes overfitting automatically.

