## Exercise 7.4: GIGO Simulation
Replicate the noise simulation with $n = 50$, $n = 200$, and $n = 500$ (20 noise predictors each). How does sample size affect the number of false positives?

::: {.callout-tip collapse="true"}
## Hint
Adapt the GIGO simulation from @sec-ch7-gigo. Write a function that takes `n` as input and runs the simulation. Use `purrr::map_dfr()` to loop over the three sample sizes. Larger samples give stepwise regression more power, but also more chance to detect spurious effects --- think about what you expect to happen.
:::


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code  code-fold="true" code-summary="Show Solution"}
set.seed(640)
n_sims <- 100
p <- 20

run_gigo <- function(n, n_sims, p) {
  purrr::map_int(1:n_sims, function(i) {
    noise_data <- as.data.frame(matrix(rnorm(n * (p + 1)), nrow = n))
    names(noise_data) <- c("y", paste0("x", 1:p))
    null_m <- lm(y ~ 1, data = noise_data)
    full_m <- lm(y ~ ., data = noise_data)
    step_m <- suppressWarnings(
      step(null_m, scope = list(lower = null_m, upper = full_m),
           direction = "both", trace = 0))
    length(coef(step_m)) - 1
  })
}

gigo_results <- purrr::map_dfr(c(50, 200, 500), function(n) {
  res <- run_gigo(n, n_sims, p)
  tibble(
    n = paste0("n = ", n),
    Mean_Selected = round(mean(res), 2),
    Pct_At_Least_1 = paste0(round(100 * mean(res >= 1), 1), "%")
  )
})

gigo_results |>
  kable(
    col.names = c("Sample Size", "Mean Predictors Selected", "% with >= 1 Predictor"),
    caption = "GIGO simulation: false positive rates across sample sizes"
  )
```

